# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: zigbee-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] The phrase **smart home** refers to home automation devices that have internet access.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] Home automation, a broader category, includes *any* device that can be monitored or controlled via wireless radio signals, not just those having internet access.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] When connected with the Internet, home sensors and activation devices are an important constituent of the Internet of Things ("IoT").
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] A home automation system typically connects controlled devices to a central smart home hub (sometimes called a "gateway").
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] The user interface for control of the system uses either wall-mounted terminals, tablet or desktop computers, a mobile phone application, or a Web interface that may also be accessible off-site through the Internet.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] Early home automation began with labor-saving machines.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] Self-contained electric or gas powered home appliances became viable in the 1900s with the introduction of electric power distribution and led to the introduction of washing machines (1904), water heaters (1889), refrigerators (1913), sewing machines, dishwashers, and clothes dryers.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] In 1975, the first general purpose home automation network technology, X10, was developed.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] It is a communication protocol for electronic devices.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] It primarily uses electric power transmission wiring for signalling and control, where the signals involve brief radio frequency bursts of digital data, and remains the most widely available.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] By 2012, in the United States, according to ABI Research, 1.5 million home automation systems were installed.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] Per research firm Statista more than 45 million smart home devices will be installed in U.S. homes by the end of the year 2018.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] From 2018 to 2023, the number of U.S. homes equipped with smart devices grew at 10.2% per year to reach 63.43 million by 2023.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] The word "*domotics*" is a contraction of the Latin word for a home (*domus*) and the word *robotics*.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] The word "smart" in "smart home" refers to the system being aware of the state of its devices, which is done through the information and communication technologies (ICT) protocol and the Internet of Things (IoT).
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] In 2011, Microsoft Research found that home automation could involve a high cost of ownership, inflexibility of interconnected devices, and poor manageability.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] When designing and creating a home automation system, engineers take into account several factors including scalability, how well the devices can be monitored and controlled, ease of installation and use for the consumer, affordability, speed, security, and ability to diagnose issues.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] Findings from iControl showed that consumers prioritize ease-of-use over technical innovation, and although consumers recognize that new connected devices have an unparalleled cool factor, they are not quite ready to use them in their own homes yet.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] Historically, systems have been sold as complete systems where the consumer relies on one vendor for the entire system including the hardware, the communications protocol, the central hub, and the user interface.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] However, there are now open hardware and open source software systems which can be used instead of or with proprietary hardware.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] Many of these systems interface with consumer electronics such as the Arduino or Raspberry Pi, which are easily accessible online and in most electronics stores.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] In addition, home automation devices are increasingly interfaced with mobile phones through Bluetooth, allowing for increased affordability and customizability for the user.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] Customers may hesitate to bet their IoT future on proprietary software or hardware devices that use proprietary protocols that may fade or become difficult to customize and interconnect.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] The nature of home automation devices can also be a problem for security, data security and data privacy, since patches to bugs found in the core operating system often do not reach users of older and lower-price devices.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] One set of researchers say that the failure of vendors to support older devices with patches and updates leaves more than 87% of active devices vulnerable.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] Concerns have been raised by tenants renting from landlords who decide to upgrade units with smart home technology.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] These concerns include weak wireless connections that render the door or appliance unusable or impractical; the security of door passcodes kept by the landlord; and the potential invasion of privacy that comes with connecting smart home technologies to home networks.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] Researchers have also conducted user studies to determine what the barriers are for consumers when integrating home automation devices or systems into their daily lifestyle.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] One of the main takeaways was regarding ease of use, as consumers tend to steer towards "plug and play" solutions over more complicated setups.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] One study found that there were large gaps in the mental-models generated by users regarding how the devices actually work.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] Specifically, the findings showed that there was a lot of misunderstanding related to where the data collected by smart devices was stored and how it was used.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] For example, in a smart light setup, one participant thought that her iPad communicated directly with the light, telling it to either turn-off or on.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] In reality, the iPad sends a signal to the cloud system that the company uses (in this case, the Hue Bridge) which then signals directly to the device.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] Overall, this field is still evolving and the nature of each device is constantly changing.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] While technologists work to create more secure, streamlined, and standardized security protocols, consumers also need to learn more about how these devices work and what the implications of putting them in their homes can be.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] The growth of this field is currently limited not only by technology but also by a user's ability to trust a device and integrate it successfully into his/her daily life.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] Utilizing home automation could lead to more efficient and intelligent energy-saving techniques.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] To do this, researchers propose using data from sensors regarding consumer activity within the home to anticipate consumer needs and balance that with energy consumption.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] Furthermore, home automation has a large potential regarding family safety and security.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] According to a 2015 survey done by iControl, the primary drivers of the demand for smart and connected devices are first "personal and family security", and second "excitement about energy savings".
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] Home automation includes a variety of smart security systems and surveillance setups.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] This allows consumers to monitor their homes while away, and to give trusted family members access to that information in case anything bad happens.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] While there are many competing vendors, there are increasing efforts towards open source systems.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] However, there are issues with the current state of home automation including a lack of standardized security measures and deprecation of older devices without backwards compatibility.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] Home automation has high potential for sharing data between family members or trusted individuals for personal security purposes and could lead to energy saving measures with a positive environmental impact in the future.
[src:zigbee-deep/home-automation] The home automation market was worth US$64 billion in 2022 and is projected to grow to over $163 billion in 2028.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] IEEE standard 802.15.4 is intended to offer the fundamental lower network layers of a type of wireless personal area network (WPAN), which focuses on low-cost, low-speed ubiquitous communication between devices.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] It can be contrasted with other approaches, such as Wi-Fi, which offers more bandwidth and requires more power.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] The emphasis is on very low-cost communication of nearby devices with little to no underlying infrastructure, intending to exploit this to lower power consumption even more.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] The basic framework conceives a 10-meter communications range with line of sight at a transfer rate of 250 kbit/s.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Bandwidth tradeoffs are possible to favor more radically embedded devices with even lower power requirements for increased battery operating time, through the definition of not one, but several physical layers.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Lower transfer rates of 20 and 40 kbit/s were initially defined, with the 100 kbit/s rate being added in the current revision.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Even lower rates can be used, which results in lower power consumption.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] As already mentioned, the main goal of IEEE 802.15.4 regarding WPANs is the emphasis on achieving low manufacturing and operating costs through the use of relatively simple transceivers, while enabling application flexibility and adaptability.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Integrated support for secure communications.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Power management functions to adjust compromises of link speed and quality and energy detection.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Support for time- and data-rate–sensitive applications through the ability to operate with either CSMA/CA or TDMA access modes.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] The TDMA mode of operation is supported via the GTS feature of the standard.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] IEEE 802.15.4-conformant devices may use one of three possible frequency bands for operation (868/915/2450 MHz).
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Devices are designed to interact with each other over a conceptually simple wireless network.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] The definition of the network layers is based on the OSI model; although only the lower layers are defined in the standard, interaction with upper layers is intended, possibly using an IEEE 802.2 logical link control sublayer accessing the MAC through a convergence sublayer.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Implementations may rely on external devices or be purely embedded, self-functioning devices.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] The *physical layer* (PHY) provides the data transmission service.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] It also, provides an interface to the *physical layer management entity*, which offers access to every physical layer management function and maintains a database of information on related personal area networks.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Thus, the PHY manages the physical radio transceiver, performs channel selection along with energy and signal management functions.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] An optional alternative 868/915 MHz layer is defined using a combination of binary keying and amplitude-shift keying (thus based on parallel, not sequential, spread spectrum; PSSS).
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Dynamic switching between supported 868/915 MHz PHYs is possible.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Beyond these three bands, the IEEE 802.15.4c study group considered the newly opened 314–316 MHz, 430–434 MHz, and 779–787 MHz bands in China, while the IEEE 802.15 Task Group 4d defined an amendment to to support the new 950–956 MHz band in Japan.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] The first standard amendments by these groups were released in April 2009.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] IEEE 802.15.4e was chartered to define a MAC amendment to the existing standard 802.15.4-2006 which adopts a channel hopping strategy to improve support for the industrial market.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Channel hopping increases robustness against external interference and persistent multi-path fading.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] On February 6, 2012, the IEEE Standards Association Board approved IEEE 802.15.4e which concluded all Task Group 4e efforts.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] The medium access control (MAC) enables the transmission of MAC frames through the use of the physical channel.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Besides the data service, it offers a management interface and itself manages access to the physical channel and network beaconing.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] It also controls frame validation, guarantees time slots and handles node associations.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Finally, it offers hook points for secure services.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Note that the IEEE 802.15 standard does *not* use 802.1d or IEEE standard 802.15.4q-2016; i.e., it does not exchange standard Ethernet frames.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] The physical frame-format is specified in IEEE standard 802.15.4-2011 in section 5.2.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] It is tailored to the fact that most IEEE 802.15.4 PHYs only support frames of up to 127 bytes (adaptation layer protocols such as the IETF's 6LoWPAN provide fragmentation schemes to support larger network layer packets).
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] No higher-level layers or interoperability sublayers are defined in the standard.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Other specifications, such as Zigbee, SNAP, and 6LoWPAN/Thread, build on this standard.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] RIOT, OpenWSN, TinyOS, Unison RTOS, DSPnano RTOS, nanoQplus, Contiki and Zephyr operating systems also use some components of IEEE standard 802.15.4-2020 hardware and software.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] The standard defines two types of network node.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] The first one is the **full-function device** (FFD).
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] It can serve as the coordinator of a personal area network just as it may function as a common node.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] It implements a general model of communication which allows it to talk to any other device: it may also relay messages, in which case it is dubbed a coordinator (PAN coordinator when it is in charge of the whole network).
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] On the other hand, there are **reduced-function devices** (RFD).
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] These are meant to be extremely simple devices with very modest resource and communication requirements; due to this, they can only communicate with FFDs and can never act as coordinators.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Networks can be built as either peer-to-peer or star networks.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] However, every network needs at least one FFD to work as the coordinator of the network.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Networks are thus formed by groups of devices separated by suitable distances.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Each device has a unique 64-bit identifier, and if some conditions are met, short 16-bit identifiers can be used within a restricted environment.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Namely, within each PAN domain, communications will probably use short identifiers.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] A more structured **star** pattern is also supported, where the coordinator of the network will necessarily be the central node.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Such a network can originate when an FFD decides to create its own PAN and declare itself its coordinator, after choosing a unique PAN identifier.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] After that, other devices can join the network, which is fully independent from all other star networks.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Frames are the basic unit of data transport, of which there are four fundamental types (data, acknowledgment, beacon and MAC command frames), which provide a reasonable tradeoff between simplicity and robustness.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Additionally, a superframe structure, defined by the coordinator, may be used, in which case two beacons act as its limits and provide synchronization to other devices as well as configuration information.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] A superframe consists of sixteen equal-length slots, which can be further divided into an active part and an inactive part, during which the coordinator may enter power saving mode, not needing to control its network.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Within superframes contention occurs between their limits, and is resolved by CSMA/CA.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Every transmission must end before the arrival of the second beacon.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] As mentioned before, applications with well-defined bandwidth needs can use up to seven domains of one or more contentionless guaranteed time slots, trailing at the end of the superframe.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] The first part of the superframe must be sufficient to give service to the network structure and its devices.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Superframes are typically utilized within the context of low-latency devices, whose associations must be kept even if inactive for long periods of time.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Data transfers to the coordinator require a beacon synchronization phase, if applicable, followed by CSMA/CA transmission (by means of slots if superframes are in use); acknowledgment is optional.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Data transfers from the coordinator usually follow device requests: if beacons are in use, these are used to signal requests; the coordinator acknowledges the request and then sends the data in packets which are acknowledged by the device.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] The same is done when superframes are not in use, only in this case there are no beacons to keep track of pending messages.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Point-to-point networks may either use unslotted CSMA/CA or synchronization mechanisms; in this case, communication between any two devices is possible, whereas in "structured" modes one of the devices must be the network coordinator.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] In general, all implemented procedures follow a typical request-confirm/indication-response classification.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] The physical medium is accessed through a CSMA/CA access method.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Networks which are not using beaconing mechanisms utilize an unslotted variation which is based on the listening of the medium, leveraged by a random exponential backoff algorithm; acknowledgments do not adhere to this discipline.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Common data transmission utilizes unallocated slots when beaconing is in use; again, confirmations do not follow the same process.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Confirmation messages may be optional under certain circumstances, in which case a success assumption is made.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Whatever the case, if a device is unable to process a frame at a given time, it simply does not confirm its reception: timeout-based retransmission can be performed a number of times, following after that a decision of whether to abort or keep trying.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Because the predicted environment of these devices demands maximization of battery life, the protocols tend to favor the methods which lead to it, implementing periodic checks for pending messages, the frequency of which depends on application needs.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Regarding secure communications, the MAC sublayer offers facilities which can be harnessed by upper layers to achieve the desired level of security.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Higher-layer processes may specify keys to perform symmetric cryptography to protect the payload and restrict it to a group of devices or just a point-to-point link; these groups of devices can be specified in access control lists.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] Furthermore, MAC computes *freshness checks* between successive receptions to ensure that presumably old frames, or data which is no longer considered valid, does not transcend to higher layers.
[src:zigbee-deep/ieee-802-15-4] In addition to this secure mode, there is another, insecure MAC mode, which allows access control lists merely as a means to decide on the acceptance of frames according to their (presumed) source.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] The earliest attempts to reduce the amount of power required by an electronic device were related to the development of the wristwatch.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] Electronic watches require electricity as a power source, and some mechanical movements and hybrid electromechanical movements also require electricity.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] Usually, the electricity is provided by a replaceable battery.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] The first use of electrical power in watches was as a substitute for the mainspring, to remove the need for winding.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] The first electrically powered watch, the Hamilton Electric 500, was released in 1957 by the Hamilton Watch Company of Lancaster, Pennsylvania.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] The first quartz wristwatches were manufactured in 1967, using analog hands to display the time.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] Watch batteries (strictly speaking cells, as a battery is composed of multiple cells) are specially designed for their purpose.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] They are very small and provide tiny amounts of power continuously for very long periods (several years or more).
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] In some cases, replacing the battery requires a trip to a watch repair shop or watch dealer.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] Rechargeable batteries are used in some solar-powered watches.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] The first digital *electronic* watch was a Pulsar LED prototype produced in 1970.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] Digital LED watches were very expensive and out of reach to the common consumer until 1975, when Texas Instruments started to mass-produce LED watches inside a plastic case.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] Most watches with LED displays required that the user press a button to see the time displayed for a few seconds because LEDs used so much power that they could not be kept operating continuously.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] Watches with LED displays were popular for a few years, but soon the LED displays were superseded by liquid crystal displays (LCDs), which used less battery power and were much more convenient in use, with the display always visible and no need to push a button before seeing the time.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] Only in darkness, you had to press a button to light the display with a tiny light bulb, later illuminating LEDs.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] Most electronic watches today use 32.768 KHz quartz oscillators.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] As of 2013, processors specifically designed for wristwatches are the lowest-power processors manufactured today—often 4-bit, 32.768 kHz processors.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] When personal computers were first developed, power consumption was not an issue.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] With the development of portable computers however, the requirement to run a computer off a battery pack necessitated the search for a compromise between computing power and power consumption.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] Originally most processors ran both the core and I/O circuits at 5 volts, as in the Intel 8088 used by the first Compaq Portable.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] It was later reduced to 3.5, 3.3, and 2.5 volts to lower power consumption.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] For example, the Pentium P5 core voltage decreased from 5V in 1993, to 2.5V in 1997.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] With lower voltage comes lower overall power consumption, making a system less expensive to run on any existing battery technology and able to function for longer.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] This is crucially important for portable or mobile systems.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] The emphasis on battery operation has driven many of the advances in lowering processor voltage because this has a significant effect on battery life.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] The second major benefit is that with less voltage and therefore less power consumption, there will be less heat produced.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] Processors that run cooler can be packed into systems more tightly and will last longer.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] The third major benefit is that a processor running cooler on less power can be made to run faster.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] Lowering the voltage has been one of the key factors in allowing the clock rate of processors to go higher and higher.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] The density and speed of integrated-circuit computing elements has increased exponentially for several decades, following a trend described by Moore's Law.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] While it is generally accepted that this exponential improvement trend will end, it is unclear exactly how dense and fast integrated circuits will get by the time this point is reached.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] Working devices have been demonstrated which were fabricated with a MOSFET transistor channel length of 6.3 nanometres using conventional semiconductor materials, and devices have been built that use carbon nanotubes as MOSFET gates, giving a channel length of approximately one nanometre.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] The density and computing power of integrated circuits are limited primarily by power-dissipation concerns.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] The overall power consumption of a new personal computer has been increasing at about 22% growth per year.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] This increase in consumption comes even though the energy consumed by a single CMOS logic gate in order to change its state has fallen exponentially in accordance with Moore's law, by virtue of shrinkage.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] An integrated-circuit chip contains many capacitive loads, formed both intentionally (as with gate-to-channel capacitance) and unintentionally (between conductors which are near each other but not electrically connected).
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] Changing the state of the circuit causes a change in the voltage across these parasitic capacitances, which involves a change in the amount of stored energy.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] The effect of heat dissipation on state change is to limit the amount of computation that may be performed within a given power budget.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] While device shrinkage can reduce some parasitic capacitances, the number of devices on an integrated circuit chip has increased more than enough to compensate for reduced capacitance in each individual device.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] Some circuits – dynamic logic, for example – require a minimum clock rate in order to function properly, wasting "dynamic power" even when they do not perform useful computations.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] Other circuits – most prominently, the RCA 1802, but also several later chips such as the WDC 65C02, the Intel 80C85, the Freescale 68HC11 and some other CMOS chips – use "fully static logic" that has no minimum clock rate, but can "stop the clock" and hold their state indefinitely.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] When the clock is stopped, such circuits use no dynamic power but they still have a small, static power consumption caused by leakage current.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] As circuit dimensions shrink, subthreshold leakage current becomes more prominent.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] This leakage current results in power consumption, even when no switching is taking place (static power consumption).
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] In modern chips, this current generally accounts for half the power consumed by the IC.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] Loss from subthreshold leakage can be reduced by raising the threshold voltage and lowering the supply voltage.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] Both these changes slow down the circuit significantly.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] To address this issue, some modern low-power circuits use dual supply voltages to improve speed on critical paths of the circuit and lower power consumption on non-critical paths.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] Some circuits even use different transistors (with different threshold voltages) in different parts of the circuit, in an attempt to further reduce power consumption without significant performance loss.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] Another method that is used to reduce power consumption is power gating: the use of sleep transistors to disable entire blocks when not in use.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] Systems that are dormant for long periods of time and "wake up" to perform a periodic activity are often in an isolated location monitoring an activity.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] These systems are generally battery- or solar-powered and hence, reducing power consumption is a key design issue for these systems.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] By shutting down a functional but leaky block until it is used, leakage current can be reduced significantly.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] For some embedded systems that only function for short periods at a time, this can dramatically reduce power consumption.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] Two other approaches also exist to lower the power overhead of state changes.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] One is to reduce the operating voltage of the circuit, as in a dual-voltage CPU, or to reduce the voltage change involved in a state change (making a state change only, changing node voltage by a fraction of the supply voltage—low voltage differential signaling, for example).
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] This approach is limited by thermal noise within the circuit.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] There is a characteristic voltage (proportional to the device temperature and to the Boltzmann constant), which the state switching voltage must exceed in order for the circuit to be resistant to noise.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] This is typically on the order of 50–100 mV, for devices rated to 100 degrees Celsius external temperature (about 4 *kT*, where *T* is the device's internal temperature in Kelvins and *k* is the Boltzmann constant).
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] The second approach is to attempt to provide charge to the capacitive loads through paths that are not primarily resistive.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] This is the principle behind adiabatic circuits.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] The charge is supplied either from a variable-voltage inductive power supply or by other elements in a reversible-logic circuit.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] In both cases, the charge transfer must be primarily regulated by the non-resistive load.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] As a practical rule of thumb, this means the change rate of a signal must be slower than that dictated by the RC time constant of the circuit being driven.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] In other words, the price of reduced power consumption per unit computation is a reduced absolute speed of computation.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] In practice, although adiabatic circuits have been built, it has been difficult for them to reduce computation power substantially in practical circuits.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] Finally, there are several techniques for reducing the number of state changes associated with a given computation.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] For clocked-logic circuits, the clock gating technique is used, to avoid changing the state of functional blocks that are not required for a given operation.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] As a more extreme alternative, the asynchronous logic approach implements circuits in such a way that a specific externally supplied clock is not required.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] While both of these techniques are used to different extents in integrated circuit design, the limit of practical applicability for each appears to have been reached.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] There are a variety of techniques for reducing the amount of battery power required for a desired wireless communication goodput.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] Some wireless mesh networks use "smart" low power broadcasting techniques that reduce the battery power required to transmit.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] This can be achieved by using power aware protocols and joint power control systems.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] In 2007, about 10% of the average IT budget was spent on energy, and energy costs for IT were expected to rise to 50% by 2010.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] The weight and cost of power supply and cooling systems generally depends on the maximum possible power that could be used at any one time.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] There are two ways to prevent a system from being permanently damaged by excessive heat.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] Most desktop computers design power and cooling systems around the worst-case CPU power dissipation at the maximum frequency, maximum workload, and worst-case environment.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] To reduce weight and cost, many laptop computers choose to use a much lighter, lower-cost cooling system designed around a much lower Thermal Design Power, that is somewhat above expected maximum frequency, typical workload, and typical environment.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] Typically such systems reduce (throttle) the clock rate when the CPU die temperature gets too hot, reducing the power dissipated to a level that the cooling system can handle.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] Implantable medical devices represent one of the most demanding applications of low-power electronics, as they must operate reliably for years or decades inside the human body without requiring battery replacement surgery.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] Cardiac pacemakers, cochlear implants, neurostimulators, and implantable cardioverter-defibrillators are among the devices that depend critically on ultra-low power circuit design.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] Pacemakers, for example, consume only a few tens of microamperes of current, allowing lithium-iodide batteries to power the device for up to ten years or more without replacement.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] The tight power budget of implantable devices imposes stringent constraints on every subsystem, including signal acquisition front-ends, digital signal processors, and wireless telemetry links.
[src:zigbee-deep/low-power-electronics] As a result, implantable medical devices have driven significant innovation in ultra-low power integrated circuit design, and techniques developed for this field have had broad influence on low-power electronics in general.
[src:zigbee-deep/mesh-networking] A **mesh network** is a network topology in which the infrastructure nodes (i.e., bridges, switches, and other infrastructure devices) connect directly, dynamically and non-hierarchically to as many other nodes as possible and cooperate with one another to efficiently route data to and from hosts.
[src:zigbee-deep/mesh-networking] This lack of dependency on one node allows for every node to participate in the relay of information.
[src:zigbee-deep/mesh-networking] Mesh networks dynamically self-organize and self-configure, which can reduce installation overhead.
[src:zigbee-deep/mesh-networking] The ability to self-configure enables dynamic distribution of workloads, particularly in the event that a few nodes should fail.
[src:zigbee-deep/mesh-networking] This, in turn, contributes to fault-tolerance and reduced maintenance costs.
[src:zigbee-deep/mesh-networking] Mesh topology may be contrasted with conventional star/tree network topologies in which the bridges/switches are directly linked to only a small subset of other bridges/switches, and the links between these infrastructure neighbours are hierarchical.
[src:zigbee-deep/mesh-networking] While star-and-tree topologies are very well established, highly standardized and vendor-neutral, vendors of mesh network devices have not yet all agreed on common standards, and interoperability between devices from different vendors is not yet assured.
[src:zigbee-deep/mesh-networking] Mesh networks can relay messages using either a *flooding* or a *routing* technique, which makes them different from non-mesh networks.
[src:zigbee-deep/mesh-networking] A routed message is propagated along a path by *hopping* from node to node until it reaches its destination.
[src:zigbee-deep/mesh-networking] To ensure that all its paths are available, the network must allow for continuous connections and must reconfigure itself around broken paths, using *self-healing* algorithms such as Shortest Path Bridging and TRILL (Transparent Interconnection of Lots of Links).
[src:zigbee-deep/mesh-networking] Self-healing allows a routing-based network to operate when a node breaks down or when a connection becomes unreliable.
[src:zigbee-deep/mesh-networking] The network is typically quite reliable, as there is often more than one path between a source and a destination in the network.
[src:zigbee-deep/mesh-networking] Although mostly used in wireless situations, this concept can also apply to wired networks and to software interaction.
[src:zigbee-deep/mesh-networking] A mesh network whose nodes are all connected to each other is a fully connected network.
[src:zigbee-deep/mesh-networking] Fully connected wired networks are more secure and reliable: problems in a cable affect only the two nodes attached to it.
[src:zigbee-deep/mesh-networking] In such networks, however, the number of cables, and therefore the cost, goes up rapidly as the number of nodes increases.
[src:zigbee-deep/mesh-networking] Shortest path bridging and TRILL each allow Ethernet switches to be connected in a mesh topology and allow for all paths to be active.
[src:zigbee-deep/mesh-networking] IP routing supports multiple paths from source to destination.
[src:zigbee-deep/mesh-networking] A wireless mesh network (WMN) is a network made up of radio nodes organized in a mesh topology.
[src:zigbee-deep/mesh-networking] It can also be a form of wireless ad hoc network.
[src:zigbee-deep/personal-area-network] A **personal area network** (**PAN**) is a computer network for interconnecting electronic devices within an individual person's workspace.
[src:zigbee-deep/personal-area-network] A PAN provides data transmission among devices such as computers, smartphones, tablets and personal digital assistants.
[src:zigbee-deep/personal-area-network] PANs can be used for communication among the personal devices themselves, or for connecting to a higher-level network and the Internet, where one master device takes up the role as gateway.
[src:zigbee-deep/personal-area-network] A PAN may be carried over wired interfaces such as USB, but may be carried wirelessly, and specifically called a **wireless personal area network** (**WPAN**) using short-distance wireless network technology such as IrDA, Wireless USB, Bluetooth, NearLink or Zigbee.
[src:zigbee-deep/personal-area-network] The reach of a WPAN varies from a few centimeters to a few meters.
[src:zigbee-deep/personal-area-network] WPANs specifically tailored for low-power operation of wireless sensors are sometimes called **low-power personal area networks** (**LPPANs**) to better distinguish them from low-power wide-area networks (LPWANs).
[src:zigbee-deep/personal-area-network] Wired personal area networks provide short connections between peripherals.
[src:zigbee-deep/personal-area-network] Example technologies include USB, IEEE 1394 and Thunderbolt.
[src:zigbee-deep/personal-area-network] A wireless personal area network (WPAN) is a personal area network in which the connections are wireless.
[src:zigbee-deep/personal-area-network] The IEEE 802.15 working group has produced standards for several types of PANs operating in the ISM band, including Bluetooth.
[src:zigbee-deep/personal-area-network] The Infrared Data Association (IrDA) has produced standards for WPANs that operate using infrared communications.
[src:zigbee-deep/personal-area-network] Uses in a WPAN include, for example, Bluetooth devices such as keyboards, pointing devices, audio headsets, and printers that may connect to smartwatches, smartphones, or computers.
[src:zigbee-deep/personal-area-network] A Bluetooth WPAN is called a *piconet*, and is composed of up to 8 active devices, and a potentially large number of additional devices in *parked* mode, organized around a single controlling device (the *Central*), with all others (*Peripherals*) communicating through it.
[src:zigbee-deep/personal-area-network] A piconet typically has a range of 10 metres (33 ft), although ranges of up to 100 metres (330 ft) can be reached under ideal circumstances.
[src:zigbee-deep/personal-area-network] Long-range Bluetooth routers with augmented antenna arrays connect Bluetooth devices up to 1,000 feet (300 m).
[src:zigbee-deep/personal-area-network] With Bluetooth mesh networking, the range and number of devices are extended by using mesh networking techniques to relay information from one device to another.
[src:zigbee-deep/personal-area-network] Such a network doesn't have a Central device and may or may not be treated as a WPAN.
[src:zigbee-deep/personal-area-network] IrDA uses infrared light, which has a frequency below the human eye's sensitivity.
[src:zigbee-deep/personal-area-network] Infrared is used in other wireless communications applications, for instance, in remote controls.
[src:zigbee-deep/personal-area-network] Typical WPAN devices that use IrDA include printers, keyboards, and other serial communication interfaces.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The technology defined by the Zigbee specification is intended to be simpler and less expensive than other wireless personal area networks (WPANs), such as Bluetooth, or more general wireless networking standards, such as Wi-Fi (or Li-Fi).
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Applications include wireless light switches, home energy monitors, traffic management systems, and other consumer and industrial equipment that requires short-range, low-rate wireless data transfer.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Its low power consumption limits transmission distances to 10–100 meters (33–328 ft) line-of-sight, depending on power output and environmental characteristics.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Zigbee devices can transmit data over long distances by passing data through a mesh network of intermediate devices to reach more distant ones.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Zigbee is typically used in low-data-rate applications that require long battery life and secure networking.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] (Zigbee networks are secured by 128-bit symmetric encryption keys.) Zigbee has a defined rate of up to 250 kbit/s, best suited for intermittent data transmissions from a sensor or input device.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Zigbee was conceived in 1998, standardized in 2003, and revised in 2006.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The name refers to the waggle dance of honey bees after their return to the beehive.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Zigbee is a low-power wireless mesh network standard delivering low-latency communication and targeted at battery-powered devices in wireless control and monitoring applications.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Zigbee chips are typically integrated with radios and microcontrollers.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Zigbee operates in the industrial, scientific and medical (ISM) radio bands, with the 2.4 GHz band being primarily used for lighting and home automation devices in most jurisdictions worldwide.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Devices for commercial utility metering and medical device data collection often use *sub-GHz* frequencies: 902–928 MHz in North America, Australia, and Israel, 868–870 MHz in Europe, 779–787 MHz in China.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Data rates vary from around 20 kbit/s for sub-GHz bands to around 250 kbit/s for the 2.4 GHz band.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Zigbee builds on the physical layer and media access control defined in the IEEE 802.15.4 standard for low-rate wireless personal area networks (WPANs).
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The Zigbee specification includes four additional key components: network layer, application layer, *Zigbee Device Objects* (ZDOs) and manufacturer-defined application objects.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] ZDOs are responsible for tasks including keeping track of device roles, managing requests to join a network, and discovering and securing devices.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The Zigbee network layer natively supports star and tree, and generic mesh networking topologies.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Every network must have one coordinator device.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Within star networks, the coordinator must be the central node.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Both trees and meshes allow the use of Zigbee routers to extend communication at the network layer.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Another defining feature of Zigbee is facilities for carrying out secure communications, protecting the establishment and transport of cryptographic keys, ciphering frames, and controlling devices.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] For this, it builds on the basic security framework defined in IEEE 802.15.4.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Zigbee-style self-organizing ad hoc digital radio networks were conceived in the 1990s.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The IEEE 802.15.4-2003 Zigbee specification was ratified on December 14, 2004.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The Connectivity Standards Alliance (formerly Zigbee Alliance) announced availability of Specification 1.0 on June 13, 2005, known as the *ZigBee 2004 Specification*.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] In September 2006, the *Zigbee 2006 Specification* was announced, obsoleting the 2004 stack The 2006 specification replaces the message and key–value pair structure used in the 2004 stack with a *cluster library*.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The library is a set of standardised commands, attributes and global artifacts organised under groups known as clusters with names such as Smart Energy, Home Automation, and **Zigbee Light Link**.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Since its unveiling, Dotdot has functioned as the default application layer for almost all Zigbee devices.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Zigbee Pro, also known as Zigbee 2007, was finalized in 2007.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] A Zigbee Pro device may join and operate on a legacy Zigbee network and vice versa.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Due to differences in routing options, a Zigbee Pro device must become a non-routing Zigbee End Device (ZED) on a legacy Zigbee network, and a legacy Zigbee device must become a ZED on a Zigbee Pro network.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] It operates using the 2.4 GHz ISM band and adds a sub-GHz band.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Zigbee protocols are intended for embedded applications requiring low power consumption and tolerating low data rates.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The resulting network will use very little power—individual devices must have a battery life of at least two years to pass certification.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Zigbee is not for situations with high mobility among nodes.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Hence, it is not suitable for tactical ad hoc radio networks in the battlefield, where high data rate and high mobility is present and needed.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The first Zigbee application profile, Home Automation, was announced November 2, 2007.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Additional application profiles have since been published.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The **Zigbee Smart Energy 2.0** specifications define an Internet Protocol-based communication protocol to monitor, control, inform, and automate the delivery and use of energy and water.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] It is an enhancement of the Zigbee Smart Energy version 1 specifications.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] It adds services for plug-in electric vehicle charging, installation, configuration and firmware download, prepay services, user information and messaging, load control, demand response and common information and application profile interfaces for wired and wireless networks.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Zigbee Smart Energy relies on Zigbee IP, a network layer that routes standard IPv6 traffic over IEEE 802.15.4 using 6LoWPAN header compression.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] In 2009, the Radio Frequency for Consumer Electronics Consortium (RF4CE) and Connectivity Standards Alliance (formerly Zigbee Alliance) agreed to jointly deliver a standard for radio frequency remote controls.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Zigbee RF4CE is designed for a broad range of consumer electronics products, such as TVs and set-top boxes.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] It promised many advantages over existing remote control solutions, including richer communication and increased reliability, enhanced features and flexibility, interoperability, and no line-of-sight barrier.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The Zigbee RF4CE specification uses a subset of Zigbee functionality allowing to run on smaller memory configurations in lower-cost devices, such as remote control of consumer electronics.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The radio design used by Zigbee has few analog stages and uses digital circuits wherever possible.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Products that integrate the radio and microcontroller into a single module are available.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The Zigbee qualification process involves a full validation of the requirements of the physical layer.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] All radios derived from the same validated semiconductor mask set would enjoy the same RF characteristics.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Zigbee radios have very tight constraints on power and bandwidth.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] An uncertified physical layer that malfunctions can increase the power consumption of other devices on a Zigbee network.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Thus, radios are tested with guidance given by Clause 6 of the 802.15.4-2006 Standard.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] This standard specifies operation in the unlicensed 2.4 to 2.4835 GHz (worldwide), 902 to 928 MHz (Americas and Australia) and 868 to 868.6 MHz (Europe) ISM bands.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Sixteen channels are allocated in the 2.4 GHz band, spaced 5 MHz apart, though using only 2 MHz of bandwidth each.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The radios use direct-sequence spread spectrum coding, which is managed by the digital stream into the modulator.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Binary phase-shift keying (BPSK) is used in the 868 and 915 MHz bands, and offset quadrature phase-shift keying (OQPSK) that transmits two bits per symbol is used in the 2.4 GHz band.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The raw, over-the-air data rate is 250 kbit/s per channel in the 2.4 GHz band, 40 kbit/s per channel in the 915 MHz band, and 20 kbit/s in the 868 MHz band.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The actual data throughput will be less than the maximum specified bit rate because of the packet overhead and processing delays.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] For indoor applications at 2.4 GHz, the transmission distance is 10–20 m, depending on the construction materials, the number of walls to be penetrated and the output power permitted in the geographical location.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The output power of the radios is generally 0–20 dBm (1–100 mW).
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The current Zigbee protocols support beacon-enabled and non-beacon-enabled networks.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] In non-beacon-enabled networks, an unslotted CSMA/CA channel access mechanism is used.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] In this type of network, Zigbee routers typically have their receivers continuously active, requiring additional power.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] However, this allows for heterogeneous networks in which some devices receive continuously while others transmit when necessary.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The typical example of a heterogeneous network is a wireless light switch: The Zigbee node at the lamp may constantly receive, since it is reliably powered by the mains supply to the lamp, while a battery-powered light switch would remain asleep until the switch is thrown.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] In this case, the switch wakes up, sends a command to the lamp, receives an acknowledgment, and returns to sleep.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] In such a network, the lamp node will be at least a Zigbee router, if not the Zigbee coordinator; the switch node is typically a Zigbee end device.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] In beacon-enabled networks, Zigbee routers transmit periodic beacons to confirm their presence to other network nodes.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Nodes may sleep between beacons, thus extending their battery life.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Beacon intervals depend on data rate; they may range from 15.36 milliseconds to 251.65824 seconds at 250 kbit/s, from 24 milliseconds to 393.216 seconds at 40 kbit/s and from 48 milliseconds to 786.432 seconds at 20 kbit/s.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Long beacon intervals require precise timing, which can be expensive to implement in low-cost products.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] In general, the Zigbee protocols minimize the time the radio is on, so as to reduce power use.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] In beaconing networks, nodes only need to be active while a beacon is being transmitted.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] In non-beacon-enabled networks, power consumption is decidedly asymmetrical: Some devices are always active while others spend most of their time sleeping.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Except for Smart Energy Profile 2.0, Zigbee devices are required to conform to the IEEE 802.15.4-2003 Low-rate Wireless Personal Area Network (LR-WPAN) standard.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The standard specifies the lower protocol layers—the physical layer (PHY), and the media access control portion of the data link layer.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The basic channel access mode is carrier-sense multiple access with collision avoidance (CSMA/CA).
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] That is, the nodes communicate in a way somewhat analogous to how humans converse: a node briefly checks to see that other nodes are not talking before it starts.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The main functions of the network layer are to ensure correct use of the MAC sublayer and provide a suitable interface for use by the next upper layer, namely the application layer.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The network layer deals with network functions such as connecting, disconnecting, and setting up networks.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] It can establish a network, allocate addresses, and add and remove devices.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] This layer makes use of star, mesh and tree topologies.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The data entity of the transport layer creates and manages protocol data units at the direction of the application layer and performs routing according to the current topology.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The control entity handles the configuration of new devices and establishes new networks.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] It can determine whether a neighboring device belongs to the network and discover new neighbors and routers.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The routing protocol used by the network layer is AODV.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] To find a destination device, AODV is used to broadcast a route request to all of its neighbors.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The neighbors then broadcast the request to their neighbors and onward until the destination is reached.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Once the destination is reached, a route reply is sent via unicast transmission following the lowest cost path back to the source.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Once the source receives the reply, it updates its routing table with the destination address of the next hop in the path and the associated path cost.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The application layer is the highest-level layer defined by the specification and is the effective interface of the Zigbee system to its end users.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] It comprises the majority of components added by the Zigbee specification: both ZDO (Zigbee device object) and its management procedures, together with application objects defined by the manufacturer, are considered part of this layer.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] This layer binds tables, sends messages between bound devices, manages group addresses, reassembles packets, and transports data.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] It is responsible for providing service to Zigbee device profiles.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The *ZDO* (Zigbee device object), a protocol in the Zigbee protocol stack, is responsible for overall device management, security keys, and policies.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] It is responsible for defining the role of a device as either coordinator or end device, as mentioned above, but also for the discovery of new devices on the network and the identification of their offered services.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] It may then go on to establish secure links with external devices and reply to binding requests accordingly.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The application support sublayer (APS) is the other main standard component of the stack, and as such, it offers a well-defined interface and control services.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] It works as a bridge between the network layer and the other elements of the application layer: it keeps up-to-date binding tables in the form of a database, which can be used to find appropriate devices depending on the services that are needed and those that the different devices offer.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] As the union between both specified layers, it also routes messages across the layers of the protocol stack.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] An application may consist of communicating objects that cooperate to carry out the desired tasks.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Tasks will typically be largely local to each device, such as the control of each household appliance.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The focus of Zigbee is to distribute work among many different devices that reside within individual Zigbee nodes, which in turn form a network.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The objects that form the network communicate using the facilities provided by APS, supervised by ZDO interfaces.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Within a single device, up to 240 application objects can exist, numbered in the range 1–240.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] 0 is reserved for the ZDO data interface and 255 for broadcast; the 241–254 range is not in use but may be in the future.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Addressing is also part of the application layer.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] A network node consists of an IEEE 802.15.4-conformant radio transceiver and one or more device descriptions (collections of attributes that can be polled or set or can be monitored through events).
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The transceiver is the basis for addressing, and devices within a node are specified by an *endpoint identifier* in the range 1 to 240.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] For applications to communicate, the devices that support them must use a common application protocol (types of messages, formats and so on); these sets of conventions are grouped in *profiles*.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Furthermore, binding is decided upon by matching input and output cluster identifiers unique within the context of a given profile and associated with an incoming or outgoing data flow in a device.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Binding tables contain source and destination pairs.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Depending on the available information, device discovery may follow different methods.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] When the network address is known, the IEEE address can be requested using unicast communication.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] When it is not, petitions are broadcast.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] End devices will simply respond with the requested address, while a network coordinator or a router will also send the addresses of all the devices associated with it.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] This extended discovery protocol permits external devices to find out about devices in a network and the services that they offer, which endpoints can report when queried by the discovering device (which has previously obtained their addresses).
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The use of cluster identifiers enforces the binding of complementary entities using the binding tables, which are maintained by Zigbee coordinators, as the table must always be available within a network and coordinators are most likely to have a permanent power supply.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Backups, managed by higher-level layers, may be needed by some applications.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Binding requires an established communication link; after it exists, whether to add a new node to the network is decided, according to the application and security policies.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Communication can happen right after the association.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] *Direct addressing* uses both radio address and endpoint identifier, whereas indirect addressing uses every relevant field (address, endpoint, cluster, and attribute) and requires that they are sent to the network coordinator, which maintains associations and translates requests for communication.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Indirect addressing is particularly useful to keep some devices very simple and minimize their need for storage.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Besides these two methods, *broadcast* to all endpoints in a device is available, and *group addressing* is used to communicate with groups of endpoints belonging to a specified set of devices.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] As one of its defining features, Zigbee provides facilities for carrying out secure communications, protecting the establishment and transport of cryptographic keys and encrypting data.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] It builds on the basic security framework defined in IEEE 802.15.4.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The basic mechanism to ensure confidentiality is the adequate protection of all keying material.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Keys are the cornerstone of the security architecture; as such, their protection is of paramount importance, and keys are never supposed to be transported through an insecure channel.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] A momentary exception to this rule occurs during the initial phase of the addition to the network of a previously unconfigured device.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Trust must be assumed in the initial installation of the keys, as well as in the processing of security information.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The Zigbee network model must take particular care of security considerations, as ad hoc networks may be physically accessible to external devices.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Also, the state of the working environment cannot be predicted.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Within the protocol stack, different network layers are not cryptographically separated, so access policies are needed, and conventional design assumed.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The open trust model within a device allows for key sharing, which notably decreases potential cost.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Nevertheless, the layer that creates a frame is responsible for its security.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] As malicious devices may exist, every network layer payload must be ciphered, so unauthorized traffic can be immediately cut off.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The exception, again, is the transmission of the network key, which confers a unified security layer to the grid to a new connecting device.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The Zigbee security architecture is based on CCM*, which adds encryption- and integrity-only features to CCM mode.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Zigbee uses 128-bit keys to implement its security mechanisms.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] A key can be associated either with a network, being usable by Zigbee layers and the MAC sublayer, or to a link, acquired through pre-installation, agreement or transport.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Establishment of link keys is based on a master key that controls link key correspondence.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Ultimately, at least, the initial master key must be obtained through a secure medium (transport or pre-installation), as the security of the whole network depends on it.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Link and master keys are only visible to the application layer.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Different services use different one-way variations of the link key to avoid leaks and security risks.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Key distribution is one of the most important security functions of the network.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] A secure network will designate one special device, the *trust center*, which other devices trust for the distribution of security keys.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Ideally, devices will have the trust center address and initial master key preloaded; if a momentary vulnerability is allowed, it will be sent as described above.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Typical applications without special security needs will use a network key provided by the trust center (through the initially insecure channel) to communicate.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Thus, the trust center maintains both the network key and provides point-to-point security.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Devices will only accept communications originating from a key supplied by the trust center, except for the initial master key.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] According to the German computer e-magazine *Heise Online*, Zigbee Home Automation 1.2 uses fallback keys for encryption negotiation, which are known and can not be changed.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] This makes the encryption highly vulnerable.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] This ensures that all network traffic is securely encrypted even while pairing the device.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] In addition, all Zigbee devices need to randomize their network key, no matter which pairing method they use, thereby improving security for older devices.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] The Zigbee coordinator within the Zigbee network can be set to deny access to devices that do not employ this key randomization, further increasing security.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] In addition, the Zigbee 3.0 protocol features countermeasures against removing already paired devices from the network with the intention of listening to the key exchange when re-pairing.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] Network simulators, like ns-2, OMNeT++, OPNET, and NetSim can be used to simulate IEEE 802.15.4 Zigbee networks.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] These simulators come with open source C or C++ libraries for users to modify.
[src:zigbee-deep/zigbee] This way, users can determine the validity of new algorithms before hardware implementation.
